    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Juror, the Paper</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Kenneth R Powers letter responds to April 11 Public Editor column; holds that achieving 'colorblind' society is laudable goal, but claiming that race is unimportant in juror is fantasy</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>I was surprised to see that little bit of political correctness regarding jurors' race. I do think that achieving a ''colorblind'' society is a laudable goal, but claiming that race is unimportant in a juror is fantasy.</p>
        <p>The question is: Do lawyers take race into account during voir dire? In almost all cases, the answer is a resounding yes.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>I was surprised to see that little bit of political correctness regarding jurors' race. I do think that achieving a ''colorblind'' society is a laudable goal, but claiming that race is unimportant in a juror is fantasy.</p>
        <p>The question is: Do lawyers take race into account during voir dire? In almost all cases, the answer is a resounding yes.</p>
        <p>Whether that is right or wrong, desirable or undesirable, is not a question for the reporter, whose job should be to report on reality and leave everything else for the editorial pages.</p>
        <p>KENNETH R. POWERS  Barcelona, Spain, April 11, 2004</p>
        <p>LETTERS TO THE PUBLIC EDITOR</p>
      </block>
